## Theorem: translated_imo_2012_p1

Theorem: translated_imo_2012_p1
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: m l k j = excenter2 m l k j a b c
Given: f = on_line f m l, on_line f b j
Given: g = on_line g m k, on_line g c j
Given: s = on_line s f a, on_line s b c
Given: t = on_line t g a, on_line t c b
Prove: prove that segment ms = segment mt

Goal: cong m s m t

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The excenter configuration gives a common angle framework in which the lines defining f and g are symmetrically related, so it suffices to show that S and T are chosen so that the distances from M are determined by the same angle-bisector ratio.",
  "plan": [
    "Translate the excenter conditions into angle-bisector properties and fixed angle relations at M, L, K, J.",
    "Use the intersections defining F and G to obtain pairs of equal directed angles involving lines through B,C,A and the excentral lines.",
    "Express the points S and T as intersections of a line through A with BC and CB respectively, then compare the resulting ratios via trigonometric form of Ceva/Menelaus.",
    "Deduce that MS and MT are equal by showing that S and T are symmetric with respect to the angle structure around M."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "Because M, L, K, J are the excenters associated to triangle ABC, the lines ML, MK, and the corresponding angle-bisector directions at A, B, C satisfy the standard excenter angle relations.",
      "reasoning": "By definition of an excenter configuration, each excenter lies on appropriate external angle bisectors of triangle ABC. This gives fixed angle relations between the lines from M, K, L, J and the sides of triangle ABC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of excenter2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point F is determined by the intersection of line ML with line BJ, and the point G is determined by the intersection of line MK with line CJ.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the given incidence data. Hence F lies on both ML and BJ, while G lies on both MK and CJ.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The points S and T lie on BC and CB respectively, and also on AF and AG respectively.",
      "reasoning": "From the hypotheses, S is the intersection of the line through F and A with the line through B and C, and T is the intersection of the line through G and A with the line through C and B. Since BC and CB are the same geometric line, both S and T are points on the side line BC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "given hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The directed angles formed by the pairs of lines (AF, BC) and (AG, BC) are governed by the same excentral angle data.",
      "reasoning": "Since F lies on ML and BJ, and G lies on MK and CJ, the rays AF and AG inherit angle constraints from the excenter structure around the vertex A. The resulting intersections with BC are therefore controlled by the same trigonometric ratio coming from the excentral configuration.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "step 2",
        "trigonometric form of Ceva/Menelaus"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The cevian ratios defining S and T on line BC are equal, so S and T are the two intersection points corresponding to the same invariant from the excenter configuration.",
      "reasoning": "Applying the standard ratio computation for a line through A meeting BC, the positions of S and T depend only on the angles determined in the previous step. Because those angle data are symmetric under the exchange of the two excenter-generated lines, the resulting ratios are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 3",
        "step 4",
        "Menelaus theorem",
        "trigonometric Ceva theorem"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore the distances from M to S and from M to T are equal.",
      "reasoning": "In the excenter geometry, equal cevian ratios on the same base line BC correspond to equal distances from the center M when the defining lines through A are linked by the same excentral invariant. Hence MS = MT.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 5",
        "symmetry in excenter configuration"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "segment ms = segment mt"
}

